# ⚡ Energy Recovery Arbitrage
*The semiconductor industry has optimized compute for 60 years. Not once has it asked what happens to the energy afterward.*

The global data center industry consumes ~400 TWh of electricity per year, discarding ~40% of it — 160 TWh — as waste heat, equivalent to the entire annual electricity consumption of the United Kingdom. This repository documents the architecture, metrics, and prior art for a fundamentally different approach: treating post-computation thermal energy not as a disposal problem, but as a recoverable asset. The industry's current end-to-end efficiency is approximately 2%. The recovery rate is exactly 0%.

## ✨ Features

- **Net FLOPS Metric** — Introduces `FLOPS_net = TFLOPS / (W_consumed − W_recovered)`, the only single-number metric that captures true cost of ownership at scale, replacing the structurally blind FLOPS/Watt benchmark.
- **Full Power Trace Analysis** — Follows every watt from grid input through PDU, VRM, board distribution, and silicon to quantify exactly where 98% of energy is lost before performing useful work.
- **$11.2B Waste Quantification** — Rigorous bottom-up accounting of the dollar value of thermally discarded energy across global data center infrastructure at $0.07/kWh.
- **160 TWh Recovery Target** — Maps the recoverable thermal budget against real-world national energy baselines to contextualize the magnitude of the opportunity.
- **Prior Art Corpus** — Structured documentation of existing thermal recovery approaches, WHR (waste heat recovery) technologies, and the gaps in current semiconductor roadmaps.
- **Architecture-Agnostic Framework** — Applies to air-cooled, liquid-cooled, and immersion-cooled deployments, from hyperscale cloud to edge inference hardware.
- **Benchmark Blind-Spot Audit** — Systematic analysis of why every major industry performance standard (SPECpower, MLPerf, Green500) fails to penalize thermal waste, and what a corrected standard would look like.

## 🏗️ Architecture

The project is organized around three analytical layers. The **Measurement Layer** establishes the power trace model — from grid input to useful computation — and formalizes the net energy efficiency metric. The **Quantification Layer** aggregates global data center telemetry, utility cost models, and thermal output estimates to produce auditable waste valuations. The **Recovery Layer** surveys and categorizes prior art across thermoelectric generation, heat reuse (district heating, industrial process heat), phase-change capture, and on-chip thermal harvesting, mapping each technology against the recoverable watt budget identified in layer one.

| Layer | Scope | Key Output |
|---|---|---|
| Measurement | Per-chip / per-rack power trace | End-to-end efficiency model |
| Quantification | Global fleet / annual aggregation | $11.2B waste valuation |
| Recovery | Technology landscape & prior art | WHR opportunity map |

